diately to halt the risk of women being left behind as the two crises continue into 2022. The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) and the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women (UN Women) sincerely thank the 2,200 women in Myanmar who provided valuable insights and gave their time to take part in this survey. 1 Table of Contents Acronyms 4 Executive Summary 5 1. Introduction 10 1.1 Context 10 1.2 Scope and objective of the study 11 1.3 Background 11 2. Methodology 13 3. Limitations 15 3.1 Weaknesses of interview methods 15 3.2 Comparisons with other data sources 16 4. The impact of violence on women 17 4.1 Living in the midst of violence 17 4.2 Feelings of insecurity 21 4.3 Physical violence at home since March 2020 23 5. The impact of COVID-19 and the military takeover on women\u2019s health 28 5.1 Attitude to health services 28 5.2 COVID-19: Infection, deaths, vaccination and information 30 5.3 Access to pregnancy and childbirth services since March 2020 34 6. The economic impact of COVID-19 and the military takeover on women 35 6.1 Changes in household income 35 6.2 Coping mechanisms to help deal with falling incomes 38 6.3 Cutting back on food consumption 40 6.4 The impact on paid work 43 6.5. Domestic work and unpaid care 46 6.6. Decision-making within the home 49 7. In their own words 51 8. Conclusion 52 References 54 Annex 1. Sampling methodology and response rate 55 Annex 2. Comparing the coping strategies 57 Annex 3. Tables 59 2 LIST OF TABLES Table 4.1: Feels safe during the day in own ward/village (percent) Table 4.2: Feels safe during the day outside own ward/village (percent) Table 4.3: Noticed violence against women by family members in neighbourhood since COVID-19 began in March 2020 (percent) Table 4.4: Knows a girl or woman who has sought support against domestic violence since COVID-19 began in March 2020 (percent) Table 5.1: Opinion about accessing health services in last one month (percent) Table 5.2: Any w