y takeover, UNFPA stated, \u201c688,422 women are currently pregnant in Myanmar, and it is estimated that nearly 248 preventable maternal deaths may occur in the next month if they are not able to access appropriate emergency obstetric care.\u201d34 Delays and fear", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8c9df27f-8f67-43f9-890c-eec12d332bb8": {"__data__": {"id_": "8c9df27f-8f67-43f9-890c-eec12d332bb8", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Regressing Gender Equality in Myanmar: Women living under the Pandemic and Military rule", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "47b307513506649151753c67afc8336266d1e269c3b356b3bc80517d1cf9303d"}, "3": {"node_id": "58f853f7-72a8-442c-8b20-cca72685f454", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5d3e3dbe10cf700de4af2b4e68c287b52c9a6dc0448f6b8b0561ba2e5271751b"}}, "hash": "4c8cebfec111253581e07c9fcd88351313c57f4fd102d19392c56d7f056f7364", "text": "of travelling to reach emergency care are contributing to the problem. 5.3.2 Access to health services by pregnant or breastfeeding women In the survey, 4.8 percent of women had a pregnancy or childbirth issue for which public or private health services could not be accessed; for pregnant or breastfeeding women,35 this increases to 11.1 percent (Figure 5.7). Figure 5.7: Had a pregnancy or childbirth issue for which public or private health services could not be accessed since March 2020 (percent) the rate of pregnant and breastfeeding women who could not access public or private health services is statistically higher in states and urban areas (Figure 5.7). Historically, there have been fewer health facilities available in the states. Health services in regions started from a higher point, but, in the last few months, access has become particularly problematic. 1 out of 10 currently pregnant or breastfeeding women had a pregnancy or childbirth issue for which public or private health services could not be accessed. 4.8 11.1 8.2 3.6 7.0 3.8 All women Pregnant/breast feeding States Regions Urban Rural \u201cIt is more difficult for pregnant women in the refugee camps because there are no clinics or hospitals.\u201d 53-year- old from Kayah. \u201cPregnant women are not vaccinated. It is also difficult to go to the hospital when giving birth. No longer safe to go anywhere.\u201d 47-year-old from Sagaing. 35 6. The economic impact of COVID-19 and the military takeover on women 6.1 Changes in household income 6.1.1 Background Globally, for the last two decades, extreme poverty had been declining. Then came COVID- 19 and, with it, massive job losses, shrinking economies and loss of livelihoods, particularly affecting women. Weakened social protection systems left many of the poorest without a safety net.36 It is estimated that the pandemic will push 96 million people into extreme poverty by 2021, 47 million of whom are women and girls. This will bring to 435 million the total number of women and girls living on $1.90 or less.37 The pandemic-induced poverty surge will also widen the gender poverty gap. This means that more women will be pushed into extreme poverty than men.38 This is especially the case among women aged 25 to 34, who are at the height of their productive and family formation period. In 2021, it is expected that there will be 118 women aged 25 to 34 in extreme poverty for every 100 men aged 25 to 34 in extreme poverty globally. In Myanmar, between 2005 and 2017, the poverty rate was effectively cut in half, from 48 percent to 24 percent.39 However, now there is a strong chance that these gains will be overturned in a few short years. UNDP\u2019s People\u2019s Pulse survey40 and a recently updated poverty analysis41 both show the dismal way in which Myanmar\u2019s most vulnerable are experiencing and trying to deal with the economic impacts of COVID-19 and the military takeover of the government. The poverty analysis reported that the highest number of poor people will be living in Ayeyarwady, followed by Yangon and Sagaing. Meanwhile, the greatest amount of funds needed to bring the poor over the poverty line will be needed in Yangon, due to the large population there and the depth of their poverty. 6.1.2 Changes in household income Figure 9.1 shows that, during HVS 2020, a substantial proportion of the households experienced a drop in income (83.3 percent) from March 2020, when COVID-19 began in Myanmar and when the Household Vulnerability Survey (HVS) interview took place six months later. The People\u2019s Pulse asked people whether their incomes had fallen since the military takeover; 73.6 percent stated that this was the case (Figure 6.1). Women in the survey were also asked whether their household income had fallen since the military takeover; here, the percentage, decreased a little, to 67 percent. This could be seen as the first signs of \u2018bottoming out\u2019. It could also be that the survey is not fully reaching some parts of society who are still seeing their incomes fall. Figure 6.2 shows distinct urban/rural differences, with rural households experiencing a continual decline in their incomes.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "58f853f7-72a8-442c-8b20-cca72685f454": {"__data__": {"id_": "58f853f7-72a8-442c-8b20-cca72685f454", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Regressing Gender Equality in Myanmar: Women living under the Pandemic and Military rule", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "47b307513506649151753c67afc8336266d1e269c3b356b3bc80517d1cf9303d"}, "2": {"node_id": "8c9df27f-8f67-43f9-890c-eec12d332bb8", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regressing-gender-equality-myanmar-women-living-under-pandemic-and-military-rule", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4c8cebfec111253581e07c9fcd88351313c57f4fd102d19392c56d7f056f7364"}}, "hash": "5d3e3dbe10cf700de4af2b4e68c287b52c9a6dc0448f6b8b0561ba2e5271751b", "text": "36 Figure 6.1: Change in household income over time (percent)42 Figure 6.2: Percentage reporting a fall in household income over time, by urban/rural 83.3 73.6 67.0 14.9 18.1 29.1 1.8 8.3 3.9 HVS, 