of COVID-19, and the development of national response and mitigation strategies. RBAP promoted regional dialogue platforms to share experiences and enrich knowledge and learning. We boosted the use of innovation, experimentation, and the leveraging of digital technologies for social service delivery and enhancing the interface between citizens and government. Many of these innovations are here to stay and grow. They position UNDP as a responsive partner attuned to the needs and priorities of its programme countries. 1,240 INNOVATION-ORIENTED SOCIAL ENTERPRISES LAUNCHED OR IMPROVED EMPLOYED INNOVATIVE SOLUTIONS 86% PIVOTED THEIR BUSINESS STRATEGY 87% 9,500 YOUNG ENTREPRENEURS HELPED TO STAY AFLOAT DESPITE COVID-19 CHALLENGES 28 YOUTH ENTREPRENEURS SUPPORTED ACROSS COUNTRIES YOUTH-LED BUSINESSES PROVE RESILIENT TO THE PANDEMIC: YOUTH-LED BUSINESSES Empowering Youth Entrepreneurs 18 E-GOVERNANCE SOLUTIONS Digital Transformation Development Solutions 12 E-LEARNING PLATFORMS 23 DATA COLLECTION SOLUTIONS 130 SOLUTIONS ADOPTED IN 14 E-HEALTH SYSTEM SOLUTIONS 17 COUNTRIES [ 8 ] [ 9 ] In 2020-2021, UNDP delivered US $1.618 million in Asia and the Pacific, of which more than 90 per cent came from non-core resources from our strong partnerships at the country, regional and global levels. RBAP DELIVERY BY FUNDING SOURCE 2020 & 2021* - US$1,618M 7% REGULAR RESOURCES 93% OTHER RESOURCES 49.46% 19.73% 4.92% 1.96% 0.25% 6.18% 0.04% 10.51% LOCAL COST SHARING OTHER RESOURCES OTHER TRUST FUNDS 0.02% THEMATIC TRUST FUNDS THIRD PARTY COST SHARING VERTICAL TRUST FUNDS EC COST SHARING EC TRUST FUNDS FUNDING WINDOWS Financial resources to support COVID-19 response came from repurposing US $96 million, and US $131 million were mobilized resources. The largest focus was on health systems support (over 40 per cent), followed by inclusive and integrated crisis management and social protection, which underscored the immediate needs of the countries. At the same time, longer-term objectives of a